Kenneth","last_name":"Ransom","middle_name":"Malcolm","married_names":[],"nickname":"Cap"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Built his own 30-foot yawl, sailed 8000 miles","body":"At twenty-two in 1898 he built his own thirty-foot yawl 'Gazelle' and sailed her with three companions from Lake Michigan down the Mississippi to New Orleans, across the Gulf, up the Atlantic coast to New York, and through the Erie Canal back to home port St Joseph Michigan. The twenty-month voyage covered more than eight thousand miles."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Indian Rocks Beach bridge tender for 25 years","body":"After his sailing journey he returned in 1910 to Indian Rocks Beach Florida — a stop remembered from the Gazelle voyage. He served as bridge tender at the wooden bridge there for twenty-five years until his 1933 retirement, living in a small cabin midway across the bridge where 'kids went to Cap on the bridge with their troubles and their broken toys.'"},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Raised American flag every day after Pearl Harbor","body":"After Pearl Harbor he raised the American flag over the Indian Rocks Beach bridge every day — 'buying new ones from his own pocket money as they wore out.' The daily flag-raising continued through his later retirement years."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Doubleday published 'A Year on a Yawl'","body":"American Boy magazine editor W C Sprague persuaded him to write his sailing experience as an eighteen-month serial. Doubleday Page & Co published the result as 'A Year on a Yawl,' which also ran as a serial in seven newspapers."}],"slug":"kenneth-ransom-1876"},"X00928":{"id":"X00928","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_fro